               <desc type="site-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000063-2">Longmen monastery, formerly known as Fahua monastery (法華寺), is located in the north of Longmen Monastery Village, Shichengcun, and is a major historical and cultural site protected at the national level. One significance of Longmen monastery is its long history: it has spanned six dynasties — <term subtype="dynasty" ref="/keyword/k000026">Five Dynasties</term>, <term subtype="dynasty" ref="/keyword/k000043">Later Tang</term>, <term subtype="dynasty" ref="/keyword/k000074">Song</term>, <term subtype="dynasty" ref="/keyword/k000036">Jin</term>, <term subtype="dynasty" ref="/keyword/k000101">Yuan</term>, <term subtype="dynasty" ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming</term>, and <term subtype="dynasty" ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term>. According to the stele inscription, it was first constructed in the second year of the Eastern Wei Wuding reign period (544 CE), imperially patronized by the Northern Qi emperor Gao Yang (550 CE) (Miller 2011, 179). It experienced large-scale expansions in both the Later Tang and Northern Song dynasties. The scale of the monastery reached its peak in the first year of Jianlong reign period (960), having “hundreds of halls and mansions'' (Diàntáng liáo shě shù yíng bǎi jiān “殿堂寮舍数盈百间”) (Guojia wenwuju 2006, 304). During the Taiping Xingguo reign period of the northern Song Dynasty (977-984), the monastery was granted an official name plaque “Longmenshan huiriyuan” (龙门山惠日院) by Zhao Kuangyi (Miller 2011, 179). The monastery continued to receive patronage and has undergone several renovations in the following dynasties (Jin, Yuan, Ming, and Qing): more ritual halls were added in Jin and Yuan, and more subsidiary structures were added in Ming and Qing (Miller 2011, 179). The monastery covers an area of 5,070 square meters. It sits north and faces south, adopting a three-axis layout (east, middle, and west respectively). Each axis is composed of three halls with two enclosed <term ref="/keyword/k000012">courtyards</term>, dividing the complex into the front courtyard, middle courtyard, and back courtyard, which are set into a hillside. The central axis buildings include Mount Gate (Tianwang Hall), Mahavira Hall (Main Hall), Dipankara Buddha Hall (back hall), and Thousand Buddha Pavilion (destroyed), which are framed by the east and west corridor rooms, east and west side halls, and east side bell tower, etc.; the east axis buildings include five Sacred Monk halls, seven Water and Land halls, and ancillary buildings such as meditation halls, monks’ cells, and stables; on the west axis, there are ancillary buildings such as monks’ cells and warehouses. There are more than 10 funeral pagodas (muta 墓塔) of monks in the Song, Yuan, Ming, and Qing dynasties remaining in the west gully (xigou 西沟) of the monastery. The monastery preserves 1 dharani sutra pillar in the third year of Qianzheng reign period (950), 9 Ming steles, 13 Qing steles, and 34.10 square meters of meticulous and heavily colored frescoes (Guojia wenwuju 2006, 304).
                  </p>
